text: Got my hands on some Ryazhenka recently (fermented baked milk) and it's incredible. Simply dazzling what a great variety of products you can obtain from dairy alone. Although I am not sure if it's approved (bacterially cultured milk) or not (it's thermally processed) by Sol Brah.

It's slightly but noticeably sweet and caramel-y, you can drink it like kefir but it's a lot thicker than regular milk, best way I can describe it is like if regular milk took just a few steps towards becoming sweetened condensed milk
It's cool how in East Asia everyone just sort of accepts machines have souls
If you do less than 7000 steps at work your job is probably fake ngl

It shows the increasing digitalization of life, where everything works with buttons and touchscreens, handles being part of older analog systems. A subconscious aversion to handles and pulling movements also reflects decreasing grip strength and mass nervous system degeneration.

If you hang out at home improvement stores, you'll notice nowadays a lot of kitchen cabinets have "push to open" drawers where you have to press and a spring mechanism opens them, many don't have handles. Really horrible development reflecting greater societal sickness and decay.

2019 Landshark would just say push to open kitchen cabinets and drawers are satanic. They go against everything that I stand for. You should pull stuff to open it. It's just the natural order of things. If anything kitchen cabinet doors should be harder to open, require strength.
Thought so too actually but he would say something smarter ...
The Dreams in the Witch House

Nothing ruins the mood of a place like AC. Even in winter an air conditioned room is nothing like the coziness of a wood-burning stove or even an old school radiator that creates a temperature gradient through space. Air conditioning is the heating equivalent of a digital reality

I recall in New Orleans specifically old school houses were built in a certain way to create an air current and maximize the air flow to keep the place cool in summer. And to bigger guys like us air conditioning means most buildings are uncomfortably warm even in winter months...
Any time my mom mentions Ray Peat, she adds "may God rest his soul", like he's a dead family member
